              "text": "In Python, default arguments are evaluated only once at the time the function is defined, not every time the function is called. Because a list is a \"mutable\" object, the same list instance is reused across every call to the function. If you call `add_items(1)` and then `add_items(2)`, the second call will return `[1, 2]` instead of just `[2]`.\n\nTo fix this, you should set the default value to `None` and create a new list inside the function if no list was provided.\n\ndef add_items(a, b=None):\n    if b is None:\n        b = []\n    b.append(a)\n    return b",
